The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | London book mart, ahoy! 
                                                                                                               London book mart, ahoy! 
                              The London Book Fair, 2008                            
	India is the market focus at this years London Book Fair, to be held at the Earls Court Exhibition Centre in central London between April 20 and 22.         
	London Book Fair, in its 38th year now, brings together authors, booksellers, publishers, librarians and others involved in book production worldwide.         
	The market focus programme is aimed at giving authors and publishers of the focus country an international exposure and highlight the opportunities of doing business there. To make the Indian presence at London Book Fair a success, the British Council, in association with Sahitya Akademi and NGO Capexil, is bringing together over 45 leading Indian writers, translators, critics and academicians, who will take part in the fair.         
	The writers include Javed Akhtar, Sunil Gangopadhyay, Amit Chaudhuri, Namdeo Dhasal, Ramachandra Guha, Jaishree Misra, Daljit Nagra, Anita Nair, Bhalchandra Nemade, Nandan Nilekani, K. Satchidanandan, Shankar, Vikram Seth and Pavan K. Varma, who will take part in a series of 10 seminars and readings at the book fair.        
	Sujata Sen, the director (East India) of British Council, said the market focus comes at a time when Indian writing is coveted, read and followed internationally. Our programme will reveal why India is such an exciting market for writing, reading and publishing.         
	In the Indian contingent are eight authors with a Calcutta connect  author Sunil Gangopadhyay; author Amit Chaudhuri; journalist and author Antara Dev Sen; book reviewer and author Neel Mukherjee; associate director of Brick Lane and teacher Sangeeta Datta; author Shankar; filmmaker and theatreperson Suman Mukherjee (of Chaturanga fame) and scholar and Jadavpur University teacher Supriya Chaudhuri.        
	This year, Amartya Sen will speak at the inauguration, called the Chairmans Breakfast.                    A STAFF REPORTER                                                                                                                                                                   
